Thence it passed into meaning what we call “ compound interest.'' We have already seen that Caesar had forbidden any arrears of interest to be calculated in estimating a debtor's obligation. Similar laws had been passed before his time, and the law of Genucius may really have been one of them. Livy perhaps used the expression “ fenerari '³ loosely, or may have² simply taken it from Annalists who did not clearly understand the matter. The tribune’s law may have been only an antici- pation of Caesar’s legislation‚ and not a sweeping prohibition of usury altogether.
